               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-274-person2359">
                  MICHAEL 
                  COLLINS
               <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2359" type="surname" value="COLLINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2359" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2359" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a labourer. On the 29th of September I saw the prisoner at the <placeName id="t18300415-274-crimeloc1514">Castle, in the Broadway</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-274-crimeloc1514" type="placeName" value="Castle, in the Broadway"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-274-crimeloc1514" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-274-off1512 t18300415-274-crimeloc1514"></join>; he came and sat down close against me; my clothes were then in my box up stairs, as I lodged at that house - all the articles stated were in my box except my hat, and that was gone likewise, and an old hat left in its place which I knew was the prisoner's; the prisoner was gone when I missed them, and I have seen none of them since -Tattersal's things were in my box in my care.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. What intercourse with me had you, that you knew the hat was mine? A. Because you wore it on the watch with me, and you had it on that morning - I took particular notice of it; I could swear to it from all the hats I ever saw in my life - it was at nine o'clock when you were first in company with me that morning; afterwards two other men came in, and Johnson and they went to get their breakfasts, I believe.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-274-person2360">
                  JOHN 
                  WOODS
               <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2360" type="surname" value="WOODS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2360" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2360" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 29th of September I was standing on the Broadway pavement, and saw the prisoner going from towards the house where Collins lodged to his own lodging, it was about half-past eleven o'clock; he had a very large bundle with him tied up in a red shawl, which I have seen Collins wear round his neck; I saw about his trousers a parcel, which appeared about the size of a man's arm, and part of a gown tail hung over his boot - he saw it as he knocked at the door, and tucked it in.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Was not that the time you ought to have stopped such a man? Witness. I ought to have done it, and you are the man.</p>

               <p>Prisoner. He is a man who ought not to be allowed to give evidence; he would come home at all hours of the night, and has a wife and child he is bringing up in a bad manner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-274-person2361">
                  PHILIP 
                  ANDREWS
               <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2361" type="surname" value="ANDREWS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2361" type="given" value="PHILIP"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2361" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I had a warrant against the prisoner on the 7th of April on another charge; on his examination at Bow-street I heard of this - I went to the Castle, and found Collins had removed; on Good Friday I went to his lodgings, where he gave me a list of what he had lost, and this letter which the prisoner had sent him - (read.)</p>
               <p>Friend Collins. I met to-day Johnson, and he told me that I have done something wrong in your place, which if I have I am not conscious of so doing; however, he advised me to come to you, as he was going out of town for a few days, but you may depend on it you shall be satisfied, if I have done any mischief, before three o'clock on Monday next, and I have requested of Johnson to call on you when he comes to town, hoping this will satisfy you till then; I am living here in Camberwell with a pensioner of my own regiment, as I expect to receive prizemoney every day, and should I be so fortunate as to get it before Monday you shall hear from me, as I gave Johnson up my prizeticket this morning when I met him in St. Martin's-lane - he desired me to tell you of it, and to write this letter to you; I hope you will make yourself easy till you see him or me, between this and Monday. No more at present. 
               <persName id="t18300415-274-person2362">
                  JAMES 
                  McDERMOTT
               <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2362" type="surname" value="McDERMOTT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2362" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-person2362" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>


               <p>I hope you do not mean to hurt me till you see me.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was drinking with Collins on account of the watch being broken up at the time; three or four more were in company with us; some time in the day he got tipsy, and left the company - I went to my own quarters in Westminster, and next day I went down to Chatham to draw some prize-money; in going I met Johnson, who told me Collins had been robbed, and had a suspicion I had done it; I wrote the letter, and stated as you have heard.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300415-274-verdict1515" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-verdict1515" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 38. - <rs id="t18300415-274-punish1516" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-274-punish1516" type="punishmentCategory" value="transport"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-274-defend2355 t18300415-274-punish1516"></join>
               Transported for Seven Years
            </rs>.</p>
